Yeah, that's kind of where I was conflicted. On the one hand it sort of became a, "comfy wish-fulfillment green with an iconic character" green that I wrote more of whenever I needed something sweet to work on (with maybe a little lewd here and there). On the other hand, I had sort of a Galaxy Quest idea planned out, where eventually the Star Fox "actors" would suddenly have to live out their television roles for real. Anon and Krystal would then go on adventures together through space.

I figured the second idea was a bit bigger of a scope than I was ready to commit to at the time, and after I started Happiest that kind of became my biggest priority. Now that the holidays are almost over and I have all my other Christmas greens done, I can look into juggling Cerinian Sweetheart with Happiest (or at least post it a little more frequently). Ultimately I suppose it depends on what kind of direction those who are still interested in it want to see the story go.

Bodies, not bodys. When you pluralize a noun that ends in a consonant and then a y, you change the y to an "ie." You only keep the y when it's preceded by a vowel. So "boy" becomes "boys" but "activity" becomes "activities."
>The heat from the coffee warming their bellies as the heat from their vagina was driving them mad.
Here you did a weird change in plurality that's distracting. Changing vagina to vaginas would probably make it ok.
>Not with how horny she is, still in your mind.

>>13169957
You got a lot of run-ons in there, my dude. Commas, semicolons, conjunctions, colons, and some periods would be apt. Remember that apostrophes denote possession for the most part, so "hospital's" would mean "that which belongs to the hospital. This is reversed with "it's" (it is) and its (that which belongs to it). Remember to differentiate "your" (that which belongs to you) and "you're" (you are) as well. Moving from syntax to content, it's pretty good. A good amount of detail in some of the scenes really helps connect to the reader, but spacing it out and making it easier to parse would make it more coherent overall. Pretty sweet little story, though. Keep writing!
